W11SR09: Inadequate System Logging for Stand-alone Workstations
ISM controls:
•	0580; 0582 (Relating to the generation and content of event logs).
•	0988; 1405 (Relating to the centralised collection and analysis of event logs).
•	1540 (Relating to the retention of event logs for incident investigation).
Current Risk
There is a risk that inadequate system logging, caused by the lack of centralised logging ingestion into the agency SIEM (Splunk) for stand-alone workstations, will significantly hinder security operations. The absence of real-time or aggregate log visibility will lead to delayed incident detection and response for malicious threats targeting these endpoint devices, potentially allowing an adversary to maintain persistence undetected.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
ALMOST CERTAIN	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Implement Offline Log Aggregation: Establish a recurring "Sneakernet" process to manually extract event logs from stand-alone workstations using secure, encrypted portable media for ingestion into the centralised Splunk instance.
•	Enforce Local Verbose Logging: Configure advanced audit policies on all stand-alone Windows 11 images to ensure critical security events (e.g., process creation, privilege use, and network connections) are captured locally even when disconnected.
•	Deploy Local Log Analysis Tools: Utilise local scripts or lightweight, air-gapped analysis tools on the workstations to provide immediate, on-device alerting for common indicators of compromise (IoCs).
- Treatment #1
•	Standardise local event log sizes and rotation policies to ensure at least 90 days of security events are retained on the device until the next manual ingestion cycle.
•	Utilise the Splunk Universal Forwarder in a "batch" configuration for offline environments to facilitate the structured import of log data during audit intervals.
•	Conduct monthly forensic "spot checks" on a representative sample of stand-alone workstations to validate that log integrity is maintained and no gaps in visibility exist.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
While real-time alerting remains impossible for truly disconnected systems, the implementation of a structured manual ingestion process and hardened local logging policies provides a viable audit trail. This reduces the likelihood of an incident remaining completely undetected for an indefinite period to "Unlikely." The consequence remains "Moderate" due to the inherent delay in response compared to networked systems.
